CHAPTER II.-That property does not betonq to the enemy who takes it until it has been brouqht within his fortified lines.

The property mentioned in the last chapter does not pass into the ownership of the enemy until it has been brought within his fortified lines, no matter how long it may be in his possession. The fleet of the Greeks standing off Troy may have constituted a fortified line, but a single ship does not, and there was but one ship in this case. The rule that a capture is effective only alter the captured property has been brought within fortified lines is supported by such doctore as Angelus and Salycetus. In the case before us the Spanish owners have not even lost possession. They retained it by means of the Spanish sailors who were leit on board the captured Spanish vessel. Not only was this property not brought within fortified

lines, but the Spaniards had a fair chance ol escaping.

CHAPTER IV.—That property sure to be taken is not held as taken and acquired by the enemy.

Cephalus holds that “a thing is called capturedwhen it can not escape capture,” and he applies this dictum to a certain caseos pirates. Molina applies it to wild beasts which have been injured by one hunter and ultimately taken by another. But “to pirates and wild beasts no territory offers safety.'‘ Now this principle is not true in war, of our Spaniards, for instance, who are saie in neutral territory.
